			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2427">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I got as far as the first paragraph of Deborah Y. Abramson&rsquo;s &ldquo;<a href="/article/2102">For No Good Reason</a>&rdquo; [May 1999] before I flipped the magazine shut and pushed it away. I knew what was coming; I knew her story. It didn&rsquo;t matter if some of the details differed &mdash;​ I<em> knew</em>.</p>

<p>Later, I returned to the essay, fingers gripping my coffee mug. (Coffee has almost no calories and the added bonus of artificial energy.) This time I was able to read on, to find out how the demon &mdash; &ldquo;the force that operates outside of cognition&rdquo; &mdash; works its way into another person&rsquo;s mind.</p>

<p>Bulimia is a brutal cycle. My rational side can stand outside of me and explain why the food keeps coming, and why it should come out, or not be eaten at all: &ldquo;It&rsquo;s because of your isolation. You&rsquo;re filling the deep gap left by your failed marriage,&rdquo; and so on. But I can&rsquo;t convey to others what I feel or why the cycle exists.</p>

<p>I admire Abramson&rsquo;s strength and courage in being able to tell her story. I must admit, I was hoping for a grand recovery at the end &mdash; if only to feed the demon more examples of my own failure &mdash; but the truth was better. So many of us reach for a happy ending and end up disappointed. I keep hoping for some breakthrough or book that will free what&rsquo;s left of me from the grip of this disorder. The answer, however, is in me. I just need to keep digging for it. Hopefully, with the right guidance and the knowledge that others have succeeded, I can free myself.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">C. R. H.<br>​Columbia, Maryland</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2428">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I&rsquo;m writing to cancel my subscription. Over time, <strong>The Sun</strong> has spoken less and less to me. It&rsquo;s nearing the point where I can&rsquo;t read it at all without wanting to shake some of the writers. How can Wesley J. Smith [&ldquo;<a href="/article/2076">In the Name of Compassion</a>,&rdquo; February 1999] so boldly decide for everyone that quantity matters more in life than quality? Nor can I get much out of the words of Deborah Y. Abramson, the poor little rich girl with bulimia &mdash; since she doesn&rsquo;t <em>have</em> to do anything, she has the luxury to create her own disease. Perhaps author Charles Bukowski was right when he said, &ldquo;Nobody suffers like the rich.&rdquo;</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Lita Krause<br>Minneapolis, Minnesota</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2430">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I felt an odd comfort while reading Deborah Y. Abramson&rsquo;s account of her eating disorder. Her quiet acceptance, combined with the admission that some part of her enjoys her compulsions, sounded a chord deep within me. I have never admitted to anyone the enjoyment I take from my own bizarre behavior.</p>

<p>I have gone through many different compulsions: relentlessly tearing my cuticles bloody, shoplifting, slicing myself with razor blades, strange ritual masturbation, eating nonstop, not eating at all, and &mdash; perhaps the most embarrassing of all, oddly enough &mdash; picking my nose. Some of these have been lifelong problems, while others have fallen away of their own accord. None of them has responded to psychotherapy or behavior modification. In fact, I am proud to say that I don&rsquo;t respond to behavior modification on any level.</p>

<p>Despite all of this, I appear normal. I am an intelligent and attractive young woman who enjoys life and stands up for herself. You would not know to look at me that I have grotesque behaviors I cannot control. You might notice the scarred, scabbed, bloody areas surrounding my nails, or the way my fingers never stop tearing at each other, but most people don&rsquo;t. I guess it is just too much to comprehend that these contradictions exist in one person. But the truth of me is: I am calm, gentle, and good to others, but relentless, brutal, and cruel to myself.</p>

<p>In an odd way, my compulsive side stabilizes my &ldquo;normal&rdquo;​ side, and vice versa. I can&rsquo;t imagine it being any other way.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Name Withheld<br></p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2431">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I had a hard time reading &ldquo;For No Good Reason,&rdquo; but I also couldn&rsquo;t put it down, because it was the exact opposite of my own experience. I was verbally abused by my family, and, as a result, I&rsquo;ve always wanted to eat enough to make me big and strong.</p>

<p>I was afraid as I read that Abramson would not make it through, yet I knew she had survived to tell her story. I was amazed by how she became better, and also relieved. I have gone through many trials to become a survivor myself. Hers is one of the most moving tales of struggle I have ever read.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">R. L.<br>Brookfield, Massachusetts</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2462">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I have been an avid reader of <strong>The Sun</strong> for almost two years, but no single issue has affected me as much as the May 1999 issue, where your writers touched upon bulimia, body image, and the craze for a fat-free America.</p>

<p><em>Fat.</em> The word has so many connotations, almost all of them negative. I am a married woman and an executive who owns a home. I consider myself a responsible citizen and a positive influence upon those around me. My appearance is impeccable, and I never leave home without perfect hair, clothes, makeup, and accessories. I am generally healthier than most thin people I know. Yet as a woman who weighs more than three hundred pounds, I am greeted at every turn by a subtle bias. Store clerks eye my purchases. Co-workers and bosses wonder about my capabilities and energy level. People display hurtful reactions to my size, often without saying a word. The world tells me that I am impulsive, lazy, and complacent about my health. By the media&rsquo;s definition, I am not successful because I cannot conquer my &ldquo;weight problem.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I am now pregnant. I have been horribly nauseated for the first six months, leaving me unable to eat much, and have lost twenty-five pounds. At my last doctor&rsquo;s visit, I voiced my concerns about the effects of my not eating for days on my unborn child. The doctor brushed off my questions, admonishing me that the baby could live off my &ldquo;stores.&rdquo; I fear for the health of my unborn child. I am even more afraid that she will grow up to be fat.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Deborah Brown<br>Deptford, New Jersey</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
			<div class="cta-intro">
				<h5 class="cta-title alt-ff">Thinking about writing us a letter?</h5>
				<p class="cta-text">Give in to the temptation. We love getting mail. <br><span class="xsmall">(Of course, we reserve the right to edit.)</span></p>
			</div>
			<a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor" class="cta-button b b-4 b-padding-tight small" data-label="Write Us A Letter!">Write Us A Letter!</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	

